#creating an arbitrary (random) time-series data set
set.seed(3)

x1 <- 100 + arima.sim(model = list(ar = 0.999), n = 100)
helper <- c(1:100/4 + 50)
x2 <- helper + rnorm(100, 2, 1)
y <- 1.2 * x1 + rnorm(100, 2, 1) 
y[71:100] <- y[71:100] - 20 
data <- cbind(y, x1, x2) 
matplot(data, type = "l",lwd = 3, col = c("black", "red", "blue"), xlab = "Month", ylab = "Sales (in thousands)")
legend("topleft", legend = c("US Sales", "UK Sales", "Cite Visits"), col = 1:3, lty = 1)

pre.period <- c(1, 70)
post.period <- c(71, 100)
impact <- CausalImpact(data, pre.period, post.period)
plot(impact)

head(impact[["model"]][["bsts.model"]][["coefficients"]])

## [1] "\n\nDuring the post-intervention period, the response variable had an average value of approx. 55.25. By contrast, in the absence of an intervention, we would have expected an average response of 74.80. The 95% interval of this counterfactual prediction is [73.79, 75.82]. Subtracting this prediction from the observed response yields an estimate of the causal effect the intervention had on the response variable. This effect is -19.55 with a 95% interval of [-20.57, -18.54]. For a discussion of the significance of this effect, see below.\n\nSumming up the individual data points during the post-intervention period (which can only sometimes be meaningfully interpreted), the response variable had an overall value of 1.66K. By contrast, had the intervention not taken place, we would have expected a sum of 2.24K. The 95% interval of this prediction is [2.21K, 2.27K].\n\nThe above results are given in terms of absolute numbers. In relative terms, the response variable showed a decrease of -26%. The 95% interval of this percentage is [-27%, -25%].\n\nThis means that the negative effect observed during the intervention period is statistically significant. If the experimenter had expected a positive effect, it is recommended to double-check whether anomalies in the control variables may have caused an overly optimistic expectation of what should have happened in the response variable in the absence of the intervention.\n\nThe probability of obtaining this effect by chance is very small (Bayesian one-sided tail-area probability p = 0.001). This means the causal effect can be considered statistically significant."
